{{Taxobox | regnum = [[Bacteria]] | phylum = [[Verrucomicrobia]] | classis = [[Verrucomicrobiae]] | ordo = [[Verrucomicrobiales]] | familia = [[Verrucomicrobiaceae]] | genus = ''[[Akkermansia]]'' | species = '''''A. glycaniphila''''' | binomial = ''Akkermansia glycaniphila'' | binomial_authority = Ouwerkerk ''et al''. 2016 }}
'''''Akkermansia glycanphila''''' is a species of intestinal [[mucin]]-degrading bacterium. It was first isolated from reticulated python (''[[Malayopython reticulatus]]'') feces in 2016.<ref name="Ouwerkerk2016">{{cite journal |last1=Ouwerkerk |first1=Janneke P. |last2=Aalvink |first2=Steven |last3=Belzer |first3=Clara |last4=de Vos |first4=Willem M. |title=''Akkermansia glycaniphila'' sp. nov., an anaerobic mucin-degrading bacterium isolated from reticulated python faeces |journal=International Journal of Systematic and Evolutionary Microbiology |date=1 November 2016 |volume=66 |issue=11 |pages=4614–4620 |doi=}}</ref>
==Etymology== The genus was named for Antoon DL Akkermans (1940–2006), a Dutch microbiologist recognized for his contribution to microbial ecology, and the epithet from the New Latin and Greek meaning "glycan-loving".<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Euzéby |first1=JP |title=List of Bacterial Names with Standing in Nomenclature: a folder available on the Internet. |journal=International journal of systematic bacteriology |date=April 1997 |volume=47 |issue=2 |pages=590-2 |doi=10.1099/00207713-47-2-590 |pmid=9103655}}</ref>
==Biology and biochemistry== ''A. glycaniphila'', like, ''A. muciniphilia'' is [[Gram-negative]], strictly [[Anaerobic organism|anaerobic]], non-[[motile]], non-[[spore]]-forming, oval-shaped bacterium. The typestrain is Pyt<sup>T</sup> (=DSM100705<sup>T</sup>=CIP 110913<sup>T</sup>). ''A. glycaniphila'' is able to use [[mucin]] as its sole source of carbon and nitrogen. It is culturable under the same conditions as ''A. muciniphilia'', (anaerobic conditions on medium containing gastric mucin). When grown on soft agar mucin medium, colonies appear white with a diameter of 0.7mm. The long axis of single cells is 0.6–1.0 μm. Cells are covered with filaments, and occur singly, in pairs, in short chains and in aggregates.<ref name="Ouwerkerk2016"/>
The [[bacterial genome]] of ''A. glucaniphila'' Pyt<sup>T</sup> is encoded on a single chromosome of 3,074,121 bp. The G+C content is 57.6% and contains 2,532 [[coding region|coding regions]], all 21 [[tRNA]] genes, and three complete [[rRNA]] [[operons]]. For 72% (1,811) of the coding sequences, a function could be predicted. Genome analysis revealed the presence of many mucin-degrading enzymes, of which a number are predicted to be secreted: 54 [[glycoside hydrolases]], one [[glycosyl hydrolase]], seven [[sialidases]], and three [[sulfatases]]. The Pyt<sup>T</sup> genome is predicted to encode a [[Ubiquinol oxidase (H+-transporting)|cytochrome bd ubiquinol oxidase]], indicating the potential for [[aerobic respiration]].<ref name="Ouwerkerk2017">{{cite journal |last1=Ouwerkerk |first1=Janneke P. |last2=Koehorst |first2=Jasper J. |last3=Schaap |first3=Peter J. |last4=Ritari |first4=Jarmo |last5=Paulin |first5=Lars |last6=Belzer |first6=Clara |last7=de Vos |first7=Willem M. |title=Complete Genome Sequence of Strain Pyt , a Mucin-Degrading Specialist of the Reticulated Python Gut |journal=Genome Announcements |date=5 January 2017 |volume=5 |issue=1 |doi=10.1128/genomeA.01098-16}}</ref>
==Ecology== This bacterium probably inhabits oxic-anoxic interface of the intestinal mucin layer.<ref name="Ouwerkerk2017"/> This was demonstrated for ''A. muciniphila'' Muc<sup>T</sup>.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ouwerkerk |first1=Janneke P. |last2=van der Ark |first2=Kees C. H. |last3=Davids |first3=Mark |last4=Claassens |first4=Nico J. |last5=Finestra |first5=Teresa Robert |last6=de Vos |first6=Willem M. |last7=Belzer |first7=Clara |last8=Schloss |first8=P. D. |title=Adaptation of Akkermansia muciniphila to the Oxic-Anoxic Interface of the Mucus Layer |journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology |date=1 December 2016 |volume=82 |issue=23 |pages=6983–6993 |doi=10.1128/AEM.01641-16}}</ref> 16s rRNA gene amplicon sequencing reveals that the genus ''Akkermansia'' have been detected in animals with a wide variety of GI tract anatomy (foregut, hindgut, or simple) and in diet (from herbivores to omnivores and carnivores). It has been found in mammals both wild and domesticated, and in non-mammals like birds, fish and reptiles like the Burmese python.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Costello |first1=Elizabeth K |last2=Gordon |first2=Jeffrey I |last3=Secor |first3=Stephen M |last4=Knight |first4=Rob |title=Postprandial remodeling of the gut microbiota in Burmese pythons |journal=The ISME Journal |date=3 June 2010 |volume=4 |issue=11 |pages=1375–1385 |doi=10.1038/ismej.2010.71}}</ref> Mucin types, and the glycan types expressed, vary between these organisms, but mucus a consistent feature of their intestinal tracts/<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Johansson |first1=Malin E. V. |last2=Ambort |first2=Daniel |last3=Pelaseyed |first3=Thaher |last4=Schütte |first4=André |last5=Gustafsson |first5=Jenny K. |last6=Ermund |first6=Anna |last7=Subramani |first7=Durai B. |last8=Holmén-Larsson |first8=Jessica M. |last9=Thomsson |first9=Kristina A. |last10=Bergström |first10=Joakim H. |last11=van der Post |first11=Sjoerd |last12=Rodriguez-Piñeiro |first12=Ana M. |last13=Sjövall |first13=Henrik |last14=Bäckström |first14=Malin |last15=Hansson |first15=Gunnar C. |title=Composition and functional role of the mucus layers in the intestine |journal=Cellular and Molecular Life Sciences |date=25 September 2011 |volume=68 |issue=22 |pages=3635–3641 |doi=10.1007/s00018-011-0822-3}}</ref> It may be that that mucus-colonizing microbes have a role in protecting the host against intestinal pathogens and contribute to restoration of the microbiota. <ref>{{cite journal |last1=Reid |first1=G |last2=Younes |first2=JA |last3=Van der Mei |first3=HC |last4=Gloor |first4=GB |last5=Knight |first5=R |last6=Busscher |first6=HJ |title=Microbiota restoration: natural and supplemented recovery of human microbial communities. |journal=Nature reviews. Microbiology |date=January 2011 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=27-38 |doi=10.1038/nrmicro2473 |pmid=21113182}}</ref> The complete genome of ''A. glycaniphilia'' has been sequenced.<ref name=Ouwerkerk2017/>
