{{good article}} {{Infobox astronaut | name = Thomas P. Stafford | other_names = Thomas Patten Stafford | image = Thomas Stafford.jpg | caption = Thomas Stafford (1969) | type = [[NASA]] [[Astronaut]] | status = Retired | nationality = American | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1930|09|17}} | birth_place = [[Weatherford, Oklahoma]], U.S. | death_date = <!--{{Death date and age|20YY|MM|DD|1930|09|17}}--> | death_place = | alma_mater = [[United States Naval Academy]], B.S. 1952 | occupation = [[Test pilot]], [[consultant]] | rank = [[File:US-O9 insignia.svg|25px]] [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]], [[United States Air Force]] | selection = [[List of astronauts by selection#1962|1962 NASA Group 2]] | time = 21d 03h 42m | mission = [[Gemini 6A]], [[Gemini 9A]], [[Apollo 10]], [[Apollo–Soyuz Test Project]] | insignia = [[File:Gemini 6A patch.png|40px]] [[File:Ge09Patch orig.png|40px]] [[File:Apollo-10-LOGO.png|40px]] [[File:ASTP patch.png|40px]] | Date of ret = November 1, 1975 | awards = [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|20px|link=Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]] {{Presidential Medal of Freedom}} {{CS Medal of Honor}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] [[File:Russia-Space-Medal.png|28 px|link=Medal "For Merit in Space Exploration"]] |}}
'''Thomas Patten Stafford''' (born September 17, 1930; [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lt Gen]], [[United States Air Force|USAF]], Ret.) is an American former [[United States Air Force|Air Force officer]], [[test pilot]], and [[NASA]] [[astronaut]].
After graduating from the [[United States Naval Academy]], Stafford commissioned in the [[United States Air Force]], flying the [[F-86 Sabre]] prior becoming a test pilot. He was selected to become an astronaut in 1962, and flew aboard [[Gemini 6A]] and [[Gemini 9]]. In 1969, Stafford was the Commander of [[Apollo 10]], the second manned mission to orbit the [[Moon]] and the first to fly a [[Lunar Module]] in lunar orbit, descending to an altitude of nine miles.
In 1975, Stafford was the commander of the [[Apollo-Soyuz Test Project]] flight, the first joint U.S.-[[Soviet Union|Soviet]] space mission. Stafford was a [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] at the time of the mission, becoming the first general officer to fly in space, as well as the first member of his Naval Academy class to pin on the first, second, and third stars of a general officer. He made six rendezvous in space and logged 507 hours of space flight. He has flown over 120 different types of fixed wing and [[rotary aircraft]] and three different types of [[spacecraft]].
== Early years and education == Thomas Patten Stafford was born on September 17, 1930, in [[Weatherford, Oklahoma]] to Thomas Sabert Stafford, a dentist, and Mary Ellen Stafford ({{nee|Patten}}), a former teacher. Thomas Sabert Stafford was diagnosed with skin cancer in 1944, and passed away on June 22, 1948. Mary Stafford remained in Weatherford until her death in August 1987. Stafford became interested in aviation following the start of World War II, as the nearby city [[El Reno]] has an Army Air Corps training base. Stafford began making model airplanes, and made his first flight at the age of 14 in a [[Piper Cub]]. He attended [[Weatherford High School (Oklahoma)|Weatherford High School]] and graduated in 1948.<ref name="wehavecapture">{{cite book | last1 = Stafford | first1 = Thomas | last2 = Cassutt | first2 = Michael ||author2-link = Michael Cassutt | title = We Have Capture | publisher = [[Smithsonian Institution Press]] | date = 2002 | location = Washington, DC | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=BqdqBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=We+Have+Capture |isbn= 1-58834-070-8 }}</ref>{{rp|1–4, 219}}
In his senior year of high school, Stafford was recruited to play football at the [[University of Oklahoma]], where he had received a [[Navy ROTC]] scholarship. Stafford applied to the [[United States Naval Academy]], and was accepted to the class of 1952. Stafford intended to play football for the [[Navy Midshipmen football|Navy Midshipman]], but received a career-ending knee injury during a preseason practice session. After his freshman year, he sailed aboard the [[battleship]] {{USS|Missouri|BB-63|6}}, where his roommate was his future Apollo 10 Command Module Pilot, [[John Young (astronaut)|John Young]]. Following his second year, Stafford spent a summer at [[Naval Air Station Pensacola|NAS Pensacola]], where he was exposed to naval aviation and flew in the [[North American T-6 Texan|SNJ Trainer]]. On a trip home to Weatherford, Stafford began dating his future wife, Faye Shoemaker. After his third year, he served aboard {{USS|Burdo|APD-133|6}}, a [[destroyer]] escorting USS ''Missouri''. While visiting home during his fourth year, Stafford became engaged to Faye in December 1951. In the spring of 1952, he was selected in a lottery to join the U.S. Air Force upon graduation.{{refn|group=note|The [[United States Air Force Academy|U.S. Air Force Academy]] was not yet established at this time.}} Stafford graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with honors in 1952, and was commissioned as a second lieutenant in the U.S. Air Force.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|8–13}}<ref name="usafbio">{{cite web | title = Lieutenant General Thomas P. Stafford | publisher = [[United States Air Force]] | date = February 1979 | url = http://www.af.mil/About-Us/Biographies/Display/Article/105575/lieutenant-general-thomas-p-stafford/ | accessdate = 7 February 2018 }}</ref>
==Military service== Prior to graduating high school, Stafford served in the [[45th Infantry Division (United States)|45th Infantry Division]] in the [[Oklahoma National Guard]]. Soon after, he transferred to the [[158th Field Artillery Regiment]], where he plotted targets for artillery fires.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|6}}
Stafford attended the first phase of pilot training at [[Greenville Air Force Base (Mississippi)|Greenville AFB]], [[San Marcos Air Force Base|San Marcos AFB]], and [[Connally Air Force Base|Connally AFB]], where he flew the [[North American T-6 Texan|T-6 Texan]] and the [[T-33 Shooting Star]]. While on a training mission at San Marcos AFB, he was involved in a mid-air collision with another student pilot. Stafford and his instructor were able to land successfully, but the other student pilot was killed. He graduated from pilot training on September 1, 1953, and moved to [[Tyndall Air Force Base|Tyndall AFB]] for [[F-86 Sabre]] training. In 1954, Stafford was assigned to the [[54th Fighter Squadron|54th Fighter-Interceptor Squadron]] at [[Ellsworth Air Force Base|Ellsworth AFB]], where he flew the F-86 mission for [[Arctic]] defense. In 1955, Stafford transferred to the [[496th Tactical Fighter Squadron|496th Fighter Interceptor Squadron]] at Landstuhl AFB (now [[Ramstein Air Base|Ramstein AB]]), [[West Germany]], again flying interceptor mission in the F-86 Sabre. In addition, he served as an assistant maintenance officer, developing his interest in applying for the [[U.S. Air Force Test Pilot School|USAF Experimental Test Pilot School]].<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|13–24}}
In 1958, Stafford attended the Air Force Test Pilot School at [[Edwards Air Force Base|Edwards AFB]], where he finished first in his class, and received the A. B. Honts Award. After graduation, he remained at Edwards AFB as a [[flight instructor]]. While working as an instructor, Stafford created the first civilian instructor position at Test Pilot School to ensure continuity, and co-authored the ''Pilot's Handbook for Performance Flight Testing'' and the ''Aerodynamics Handbook for Performance Flight Testing''.<ref name="nasabio">{{cite web | title = Thomas P. Stafford, Lieutenant General, USAF (Retired) | publisher = [[National Aeronautics and Space Administration]] | date = March 2014 | url = https://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/stafford-tp.html | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref> At the end of his assignment, Stafford was accepted to [[Harvard Business School]], and moved to [[Boston, Massachusetts]] in September 1962. Three days after arriving there he was accepted to [[List of astronauts by selection#1962|NASA Group Two]].<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|27–38}}
==NASA career== In April 1962, while still working as a flight instructor, Stafford applied for the next round of astronaut selection. The required interviews and medical screenings occurred over the summer of 1962 at [[Brooks Air Force Base]] and in Houston. On September 14, 1962, Stafford was selected for [[Astronaut Group 2]], alongside eight other future astronauts.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|35–40}}
===Project Gemini=== ====Gemini 6A==== {{Main|Gemini 6A}} [[File:Gemini 6 prime crew.jpg|thumb|right|Stafford (left) with his Gemini 6A crewmate Wally Schirra (1965)]] Stafford was originally scheduled to fly with [[Alan Shepard]] on the first manned Gemini mission, [[Project Gemini#Crew selection|Gemini 3]], but was replaced when Shepard was removed from the flight rotation after being diagnosed with [[Ménière's disease]]. Stafford was paired with [[Wally Schirra]] as pilot and commander, respectively, and the pair was reassigned as the backup crew for Gemini 3, and primary crew for Gemini 6.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|50}}
The original Gemini 6 mission profile involved docking with an [[Agena target vehicle]]. On October 25, 1965, Schirra and Stafford were inside Gemini 6 before liftoff when the Agena vehicle exploded on ascent. After the original mission was cancelled, it was redesignated Gemini 6A and was planned to rendezvous with the long-duration Gemini 7 mission. Gemini 7 lifted off on December 4, 1965. On December 12, 1965, Gemini 6A's ignition was followed by an immediate engine shutdown. Schirra and Stafford did not eject, and the cause of the shutdown was found to be an electrical issue and a cap inadvertently left on a fuel line.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|64–72}}
On December 15, 1965, Gemini 6A lifted off and rendezvoused with Gemini 7. The two spacecraft [[Orbital station-keeping|kept station]] for approximately five hours, coming within feet of each other. Gemini 6A splashed down on December 16, and was recovered by {{USS|Wasp|CV-18|6}}.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|70–76}}
====Gemini 9==== {{Main|Gemini 9}} [[File:Gemini Crew Welcomed by Wasp Crew - GPN-2000-001415.jpg|thumb|right|Stafford (right) and Eugene Cernan arrive aboard USS ''Wasp'' (1966)]] Prior to Gemini 6A, Stafford was assigned as the backup commander for Gemini 9 with [[Eugene Cernan]] as the backup pilot. [[Charles Bassett|Charlie Bassett]] and [[Elliot See]] were the primary crew. On February 28, 1966, both crews flew in [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38 Talons]] to [[Lambert Field]] to visit the [[McDonell Douglas]] Gemini assembly facility. Bassett and See crashed on landing, and were killed. Stafford and Cernan became the Gemini 9 primary crew, with [[Jim Lovell]] and [[Buzz Aldrin]] as their backup crew.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|75–82}}
On May 17, 1966, the Agena target vehicle went off course and was shut down before entering orbit. As there was no replacement Agena rocket, the new target for the mission was the [[Agena target vehicle#Augmented Target Docking Adapter|Augmented Target Docket Adapter (ADTA)]], which successfully achieved orbit on June 1, 1966. The Gemini 9 launch, scheduled for later the same day, was cancelled due to a computer error. Gemini 9 successfully launched on June 3, and rendezvoused with the ATDA on the second orbit. However, the shroud on the ATDA had only partially opened, and Gemini 9 was unable to dock with it. Nonetheless, Stafford and Cernan conducted orbital rendezvous maneuvers with the ATDA, including a simulated rescue of a lunar module in a lower orbit.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|85–92}}
The following day, Cernan attempted an [[extravehicular activity]] (EVA), with the primary mission of testing the [[Astronaut propulsion unit#USAF Astronaut Maneuvering Unit|Astronaut Maneuvering Unit]] (AMU). After exiting the spacecraft, Cernan quickly experienced mobility issues, followed by environmental regulation and communication issues. The EVA was aborted, and Cernan returned to the capsule after two hours. On June 6, Gemini 9 landed, and was successfully recovered by USS ''Wasp''.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|92–95}}
===Apollo program=== [[File:Astronaut Thomas P. Stafford, prime crew commander of the Apollo 10 lunar orbit mission.jpg|thumb|right|Stafford as Apollo 10 Commander (1968)]] After Gemini 9, Stafford was assigned as the backup command module pilot on Apollo 2, with [[Frank Borman]] as the commander and [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Mike Collins]] as the lunar module pilot. For his technical assignment, Stafford was tasked as an astronaut liaison for the development of Apollo guidance and navigation systems, as well as the command and service module. In late 1966, he was reassigned to Apollo 2 backup commander, with Apollo 10 crewmates John Young as the command module pilot and Gene Cernan as the lunar module pilot. While testing the command module, they received word of the [[Apollo 1#Fire|Apollo 1 fire]] and subsequent suspension of the Apollo program.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|95–105}} <ref name="cernanbio">{{cite book | last1 = Cernan | first1 = Eugene ||author1-link = Eugene Cernan | last2 = Davis | first2 = Don ||author2-link = Donald A. Davis | title = The Last Man on the Moon | publisher = [[St. Martin's Press]] | date = 1999 | location = New York | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=sBxSNMFqYPcC&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false | isbn = 0-312-19906-6 }}</ref>{{rp|1–6}}
====Apollo 10==== {{Main|Apollo 10}} In the spring of 1968, Deke Slayton announced that the previous backup crew for Apollo 2 would become the primary crew for Apollo 10. In preparation for the mission, Stafford helped design a color camera to replace the grainy black-and-white video broadcast before from space; he felt that public outreach was a vital aspect of the mission.<ref name ="Colour TV on the Moon">{{cite news | last = Lebar | first = Stanley | title = The Color War goes to the Moon | url = http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/Invent-Tech1997.pdf | accessdate = 7 February 2018 | newspaper = [[American Heritage of Invention & Technology|Invention and Technology]] | date = Summer 1997 | ref = harv }}</ref> The [[Apollo Command/Service Module#Command Module (CM)|command module]] (CM) was nicknamed "Charlie Brown"; the lunar module (LM) was nicknamed "Snoopy".<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|120–122}}
Apollo 10 lifted off on May 18, 1969. Despite heavy oscillation during ascent, Apollo 10 achieved orbit without incident, successfully docked the LM and CM, and achieved its translunar injection burn. Upon arriving in lunar orbit, Stafford and Cernan undocked in the LM and entered an elliptical orbit with a [[Apsis|periapsis]] (the closest distance) of nine miles over the lunar surface. To provide reconnaissance, the periapsis coincided with the [[Mare Tranquillitatis|Sea of Tranquility]], the intended landing site for Apollo 11. Upon ascent, the LM began turning rapidly from a misaligned switch on the Abort Guidance System; Stafford was able to regain control and conduct the burn to rendezvous with the CM. The LM docked with the CM to return the astronauts and was jettisoned. After two days in lunar orbit, the Apollo 10 began its return trajectory. Along the return, the capsule achieved a speed of {{cvt| 28547|mph}}, setting the record for the fastest speed achieved by a human being. Apollo 10 splashed down east of Samoa and was recovered by {{USS|Princeton|CV-37|6}}.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|120–135}}
==== Apollo-Soyuz Test Project ==== {{Main|Apollo-Soyuz Test Project}} [[File:ASTP Training at Star City - GPN-2002-000158.jpg|thumb|right|Stafford (right) and cosmonaut Leonov training for the Apollo-Soyuz Test Project at [[Yuri Gagarin Cosmonaut Training Center|Star City]] (1975)]]
In July 1969, Stafford replaced Alan Shepard (who had returned to flight status) as [[Chief of the Astronaut Office]]. Along with Director of Flight Crew Operations [[Deke Slayton]], Stafford oversaw assignments to the upcoming Apollo and [[Skylab]] missions until Shepard resumed the position after [[Apollo 14]] in July 1971. During this period, U.S. President [[Richard Nixon]] and Soviet Premier [[Alexei Kosygin]] agreed to the Apollo-Soyuz Test Project (ASTP). Stafford was promoted to the rank of brigadier general in late 1972, and was soon named the commander of ASTP, along with Slayton (who had also returned to flight status) and [[Vance Brand]].<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|135–156}}
Beginning in 1973, the ASTP team trained extensively in Russia and the United States. [[Soyuz 19]], carrying [[Aleksei Leonov]] and [[Valery Kubasov]], launched on July 15, 1975, at 12:20&nbsp;UTC, followed by Apollo at 19:50&nbsp;UTC. After two days in space, Soyuz and Apollo docked on July 17, where the crews met and conducted joint experiments and held press conferences. After remaining docked for 44 hours. the two spacecraft undocked on July 19. Soyuz returned to Earth on July 21; Apollo remained in orbit until July 24. While descending, the Apollo command module began filling with [[nitrogen tetroxide]] from the reaction control thrusters. The crew donned oxygen masks, but Brand lost consciousness and had to be assisted by Stafford. All crew were safely recovered aboard {{USS|New Orleans|LPH-11|6}}, and were hospitalized in Hawaii for [[edema]] (swelling) from fuel inhalation.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|156–197}}
==Post-NASA career== [[File:LtGen Thomas P Stafford Official Photo.jpg|thumb|right|LtGen Thomas Stafford (1979)]] In June 1975, before ATSP, Stafford was offered command of the [[Air Force Flight Test Center]] at Edwards AFB. He accepted and assumed the assignment on November 15, 1975. Stafford oversaw both the Air Force and NASA test facilities at Edwards AFB, as well as test ranges in [[Utah]] and [[Nevada]]. He continued to fly (including foreign aircraft such as the [[MiG-17]] and [[Panavia Tornado]]) and was involved in the interview of [[Viktor Belenko]] after his defection. Stafford also managed the development of the [[Lockheed Have Blue#Experimental Survivable Testbed|XST]], which would later evolve into the [[F-117 Nighthawk]]. In March 1978, he was promoted to lieutenant general and became Deputy Chief of Staff, Research Development and Acquisition in [[Washington, D.C.]] While working in Washington, Stafford advocated for the creation of the mobile [[MX missile]], and began developing the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit#ATB program|Advanced Technology Bomber]], the predecessor to the [[Northrop Grumman B-2 Spirit|B-2 stealth bomber]]. Stafford retired to [[Norman, Oklahoma]], on November 1, 1979.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|198–210}}
Following his retirement, Stafford served on several corporate boards, including [[Omega SA]], Gibralter Exploration, and [[Gulfstream Aerospace]]. He originally intended to reunite with his ATSP crewmates in Russia, but the 1979 [[Soviet–Afghan War|Soviet invasion of Afghanistan]], and the subsequent [[1980 Summer Olympics boycott|1980 Olympics boycott]], left them unable to travel to Russia. Stafford created a consulting firm, Stafford, Burke, and Hecker, with two recently retired general officers. In July 1990, [[Dan Quayle|Vice President Quayle]] and [[Admiral (United States)|Admiral]] [[Richard Truly]], then the [[NASA administrator]], asked Stafford to chair a committee that advised NASA on long-term lunar and [[Mars]] missions. Stafford and his team of 42 full-time members and 150 part-time members created a long-term plan with lunar missions in 2004 and Mars mission in 2012.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|211–232}} In 1992, Stafford began work as an advisor for [[Space Station Freedom]], the precursor to the [[International Space Station]] (ISS). While coordinating Russian involvement, Stafford became a technical advisor for the [[Shuttle–Mir Program]], particularly [[STS-63]] and [[STS-71]]. He also served on a review committee for the [[Progress M-34#Collision|Progress-Mir Collision]].<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|230–269}}
In 2002, Stafford published an autobiography written with [[Michael Cassutt]], titled ''We Have Capture: Tom Stafford and the Space Race''.<ref name=wehavecapture /> He also wrote the epilogue of the book ''Falling to Earth: An Apollo 15 Astronaut's Journey to the Moon'' by fellow Apollo astronaut [[Al Worden]].<ref name="fallingtoearth">{{cite web | last = Worden | first = Alfred ||author-link = Alfred Worden | title = Falling to Earth – The Autobiography of Alfred Worden | publisher = Alfred Worden | date = 2017 | url = http://www.alworden.com/falling.htm | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>
==Personal life== In 1953, Stafford married Faye Shoemaker, his fiancée from Weatherford, Oklahoma. Faye and Stafford have two daughters, Dionne (b. 1954) and Karin (b. 1957). Faye and Stafford divorced in 1985. Stafford later married Linda Ann Dishman in December 1988.<ref name=wehavecapture />{{rp|15,19,216,219}} They have two adopted sons, Michael Thomas and Stanislav "Stas" Patten.<ref name=nasabio /> Stafford enjoys [[hunting]], [[weight training|weight lifting]], [[gliding]], [[scuba diving]], [[fishing]] and [[Human swimming|swimming]].<ref name=nasabio />
==Awards and honors== {{rquote|right|This is the greatest honor of my life. I am very proud to have contributed to our nation's future in space and I am deeply grateful for the opportunity to have participated in the beginning of America's venture into the new and endless frontier.|3=Upon receiving the Congressional Space Medal of Honor.<ref name="nmmuseum">{{cite web | title = Thomas P. Stafford | work = | publisher = [[New Mexico Museum of Space History#International Space Hall of Fame|International Space Hall of Fame at New Mexico Museum of Space History]] | date = 2018 | url = http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=50 | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref>}}
Throughout his career, Stafford received numerous awards for his accomplishments. He was a recipient of the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] (AIAA) Award (1969), the [[Harmon International Aviation Trophy]] (1966), the [[National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences]] Special Trustees Award (1969), the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] [[James H. Doolittle Award]] (1979) and the [[Elmer A. Sperry Award]] (2008). Stafford received recognition from both the U.S. and Russian governments, with the U.S. [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]] (1993) and the Russian [[Medal "For Merit in Space Exploration"]] (2011).<ref name="sperryaward">{{cite web |url=http://www.sperryaward.org/recipients.htm |title= The Elmer A. Sperry Award |publisher= Elmer A. Sperry Board of Award |date= May 18, 2009 |accessdate= 22 January 2018}}</ref><ref name=usafbio /><ref name=wehavecapture /><ref name=nasabio />
[[File:Dmitry Medvedev 12 April 2011-16.jpeg|thumb|Stafford was presented with the [[Medal "For Merit in Space Exploration"]] from [[Russian President]] [[Dmitry Medvedev]] on April 12, 2011, at the [[Moscow Kremlin]]]] Stafford's military decorations and awards include: the [[Air Force Distinguished Service Medal]] with two oak leaf clusters, [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] with oak leaf cluster, [[Air Force Commendation Medal]] and [[Air Force Outstanding Unit Award]] ribbon with three oak leaf clusters. Other awards presented to Stafford include: the [[Presidential Medal of Freedom]], [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] with oak leaf cluster, [[NASA Exceptional Service Medal]] with oak leaf cluster, the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] [[Octave Chanute Award]] (1976), the Veterans of Foreign Wars National Space Award, the [[Golden Plate Award]] for Science and Exploration (1976), the [[National Geographic Society]]'s General [[Thomas D. White]] USAF Space Trophy (1975), the A. B. Honts Award as the outstanding graduate from the USAF Experimental Test Pilot School, and the [[Fédération Aéronautique Internationale]] Gold Space Medal.<ref name=wehavecapture /><ref name=nasabio />
In 2011, he was awarded the National Aeronautic Association Wright Brothers Memorial Trophy, and the Air Force Association's Lifetime Achievement Award. He joined National Academy of Engineering in 2014.<ref name=nasabio /> Stafford is an inductee of the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]], the [[U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]], the [[New Mexico Museum of Space History|International Space Hall of Fame]].<ref name="astronautscholarship">{{cite web | title = Thomas Stafford | publisher = Astronaut Scholarship Foundation | date = 2013 | url = https://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/thomas-p-stafford/ | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name="nmmuseum" /><ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref> He is a fellow of the [[American Astronautical Society]], the [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]], the [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]], and a member of the [[Explorers Club]].<ref name="aas">{{cite web | title = AAS Fellows | publisher = [[American Astronautical Society]] | date = 2018 | url = http://astronautical.org/fellows/ | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name=nasabio /><ref name="OSU Bio">{{cite web | title = Thomas P. Stafford, Lieutenant General, USAF (Retired) | publisher = [[Oklahoma State University]] | url = http://okstate.edu/apdc/ThomasStafford.htm | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref>
Stafford is the recipient of several [[honorary degree]]s. These include: a [[Doctorate of Science]] from [[Oklahoma City University]]; a [[Doctorate of Laws]] from [[Western State University]]; a Doctorate of [[Communications]] from [[Emerson College]], and a Doctorate of [[Aeronautical Engineering]] from [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]].<ref name=nasabio />
[[File:17 14 128 stafford.jpg|thumb|upright=0.75|Bust of Stafford at the [[National Museum of the United States Air Force|USAF Museum]]]]
In his hometown of Weatherford, Stafford was honored with a building at [[Southwestern Oklahoma State University]] named in his honor, the [[Thomas P. Stafford Airport]], and the [[Stafford Air & Space Museum]].<ref name="staffordairport">{{cite web | title = Oklahoma Airports | publisher = [[Federal Aviation Administration]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.notams.faa.gov/common/icao/USOK.html | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name="staffordmuseum">{{cite web | title = Stafford Air & Space Museum | publisher = [[Stafford Air & Space Museum]] | date = 2018 | url = http://staffordmuseum.org/ | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref><ref name="staffordswosu">{{cite web | title = Gen. Thomas P. Stafford at SWOSU | publisher = [[Southwestern Oklahoma State University]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.universitymaps.com/swosu/gen-thomas-p-stafford-center-stf/ | accessdate = 22 January 2018 }}</ref> The Stafford Building at the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] (FAA) [[Mike Monroney Aeronautical Center]] in [[Oklahoma City]] is named after him.<ref name="staffordbuilding">{{cite web | last = Johnson | first = James | title = Astronaut Dedicates FAA Center | publisher = News OK | date = July 1, 1989 | url = http://newsok.com/article/2271205 | accessdate = 21 January 2018 }}</ref> In Hydro, Oklahoma, 60 miles west of Oklahoma City, Stafford was honored with a [[corn maze]], which was intentionally cut to be visible from space.<ref name="cornmaze">{{cite web | title = Oklahoma corn maze honoring former astronaut is visible from space | publisher = Associated Press | date = September 24, 2018 | url = https://nypost.com/2018/09/24/corn-maze-honoring-former-astronaut-is-visible-from-space/ | accessdate = September 25, 2018 }}</ref>
== In media == * 1974 TV movie ''[[Houston, We've Got a Problem]]'' – played by himself<ref name="houston imdb">{{cite web | title = Houston, We've Got a Problem | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0071630/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref> * 1996 TV movie ''Apollo 11'' – was played by Tony Carlin.<ref name="apollo 11 imdb">{{cite web | title = Apollo 11 | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0115560/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref> * 1998 [[HBO]] [[miniseries]] ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' – played by Steve Hofvendahl.<ref name="from the earth to the moon imdb">{{cite web | title = From the Earth to the Moon | publisher = [[Internet Movie Database]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120570/fullcredits?ref_=tt_ov_st_sm | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref> * 1990 album ''[[Impurity (New Model Army album)|Impurity]]'' by British [[rock band]] [[New Model Army (band)|New Model Army]] – quotes Stafford in the song "Space"<ref>{{cite web | last1 = Sullivan | first1 = Justin | last2 = Morrow | first2 = Stuart | last3 = Tompkins | first3 = Phil | title = Space | publisher = [[New Model Army (band)|New Model Army]] | date = 2018 | url = https://www.newmodelarmy.org/index.php/the-music/lyrics/234-space | accessdate = 16 January 2018 }}</ref> * 2013 [[Pilot (The Americans)|Pilot episode]] of ''[[The Americans (2013 TV series)|The Americans]]'' on FX, played by an uncredited actor<ref name="theamericans">{{cite web |last= Seitz |first= Matt | title = The Americans Recap: Way to Commit | publisher = [[Vulture.com]] | date = January 2013 | url = http://www.vulture.com/2013/01/americans-recap-pilot.html | accessdate = 27 March 2018 }}</ref>
